 All cave entrances, also called "The Seven Sisters", have a diameter of at least 100 to 250 meters (328 to 820 feet).
 Infrared images show temperature differences between night and day, indicating that they are probably caves.
 ""They are colder during the day than the surrounding surface and warmer at night."
 "Their thermal behavior is not as uniform as that of larger caves on Earth, which often have a fairly constant temperature, but it does match that of deep holes in the ground," said Glen Cushing of the Astrogeology Team of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff, Arizona. "
 In France, voting is traditionally a low-tech experience: Voters isolate themselves in a booth and drop a pre-printed sheet of paper, on which the candidate of their choice is written, into an envelope.
 After the officials have confirmed the identity of the voter, the voter throws the envelope into the ballot box and signs the voter list.
 French election law lays down the procedure quite strictly.
 Since 1988, ballot boxes have had to be transparent so that voters and observers can attest that there are no envelopes at the beginning of the election and that no envelopes are inserted, except those of the properly counted and authorized voters.
 The candidates can send representatives to witness every part of the process, and the votes are counted by volunteers under strict supervision and special procedures.
