 Among them are medium-sized cats that eat medium-sized prey, from rabbits to antelopes and deer.
 Finally, there are many small cats (including feral cats) that eat much smaller prey such as insects, rodents, lizards, and birds.
 The secret of their success is the concept of the niche, a special task that each cat has and that ensures that it does not compete with others.
 Lions are the most social cats. They live in large groups called prides.
 The packs consist of one to three related adult males and up to thirty females and young.
 Women usually have a close relationship with each other when they live in a large family with sisters and daughters.
 Lion prides behave in a similar way to wolf or dog packs, animals that surprisingly resemble lions (but not other big cats) in their behavior and are just as deadly to their prey.
 As a versatile athlete, the tiger can climb (albeit not particularly well), swim, jump great distances and pull with the five times the strength of a strong man.
 The tiger is in the same group (genus Panthera) as lions, leopards and jaguars. These four cats are the only ones that can roar.
 The roar of the tiger does not sound like the full-throated roar of the lion, but rather like a sentence of growled words.
 Ocelots eat small animals. When they can, they prey on monkeys, snakes, rodents, and birds. Almost all the animals that the ocelot hunts are significantly smaller than it is.
 Scientists think that ocelots use their sense of smell to track and detect prey. They sniff where they have been on the ground.
 They can see very well in the dark with night vision and move unnoticed. Ocelots hunt their prey by blending in with their surroundings and then pouncing on their prey.
 When a small group of organisms (a small population) is separated from the main population from which it came (for example, if it moves across a mountain range or river, or if it moves to a new island so that it cannot easily return), they will often find themselves in a different environment than before.
 This new environment has different resources and different competitors, so the new population needs different features or adaptations to be a strong competitor than what it needed before.
 The original population has not changed at all. It still needs the same adaptations as before.
 Over time, the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, and then it looks less and less like the other population.
 After thousands or even millions of years, two populations then look so different that they can no longer be assigned to the same species.
 This process is called speciation, which simply means the emergence of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
 Plants generate oxygen that humans breathe in, and they absorb the carbon dioxide that humans exhale (that is, breathe out).
 Plants produce their food through photosynthesis using the sun. They also provide shade.
 We build our houses out of plants and make clothes out of plants. We eat mostly plants. Without plants, animals could not survive.
 The Mosasaurus was the largest predator of its time, so it feared nothing except other Mosasaurus.
 His long jaws were equipped with more than 70 razor-sharp teeth, in addition to another set in the palate, which meant that there was no escape for any animal that crossed his path.
 We don't know for sure, but he might have had a forked tongue. He ate turtles, large fish, other mosasaurs, and may have even been a cannibal.
 He also grabbed anything that came into the water; even a large dinosaur like the T. Rex was no match for him.
