 A civilization is a distinct culture shared by a significantly large group of people who live and work together, a society.
 The word civilization comes from the Latin civilis, which means civil, related to the Latin civis, which means citizen, and civitas, which means city or city state and also somehow defines the size of a society.
 City-states are the precursors of nations. A civilized culture implies the transmission of knowledge across several generations, a lasting cultural footprint and a proper distribution.
 Smaller cultures often disappear without leaving relevant historical evidence and fail to be recognized as full-fledged civilizations.
 During the Revolutionary War, the 13 states formed a weak central government based on the Articles of Confederation, which consisted only of Congress.
 Congress was not empowered to levy taxes, and since there was neither a national executive nor a national judiciary, it relied on the state governments to enforce all of its laws, which often did not cooperate.
 He also had no authority to suspend tax laws and tariffs between the states.
 The articles required the unanimous consent of all states before they could be amended, and the states took the central government so little seriously that their representatives were often absent.
