 The beginning of Taiwan goes back to the 15th century, when European sailors passed by there and documented the name of the island as Ilha Formosa or beautiful island.
 1624 The Dutch East India Company establishes a settlement in southwestern Taiwan, initiating a change in the rice farming methods of the aboriginal people and employing Chinese workers on its rice and sugar plantations.
 In 1683, Qing Dynasty (1644-1912) forces took control of western and northern coastal regions of Taiwan and declared Taiwan a province of the Qing Empire in 1885.
 In 1895, after the defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War (1894-1895), the Qing government signed the Treaty of Shimonoseki, in which it ceded sovereignty over Taiwan to Japan, which ruled the island until 1945.
