 For example, the most widely used image format in the world is 35 mm, which corresponds to the predominant film size at the end of the analog film era.
 It is still produced today, but more importantly, its image format has been adopted by digital camera image sensors.
 In fact, the so-called 35mm format measures confusingly 36mm wide and 24mm high.
 The aspect ratio of this format (divided by twelve, to get the simplest integer ratio) is therefore referred to as 3:2.
 Many common formats (the APS format family, for example) have exactly the same or a very similar aspect ratio.
 The much-maligned and often derided Rule of Thirds is a simple guideline that creates dynamism while maintaining a measure of order in an image.
 It states that the intersection of the lines that divide a picture vertically and horizontally into thirds is the most effective place for the main motif (see example).
