 Ancient China had a unique method of indicating different eras. Each time period in China and each family that was in power was a separate dynasty.
 Between the individual dynasties there were also unstable times of divided provinces, the best known of which was the Three Kingdoms period, which lasted 60 years between the Han and Jin dynasties.
 In those days, bitter wars were waged among many nobles who fought for the throne.
 The Three Kingdoms period was one of the bloodiest in the history of ancient China, with thousands of people dying in the fight for the highest throne in the grand palace of Xi'an.
 There are a lot of social and political effects like the use of the metric system, a departure from absolutism to republicanism and nationalism, and the belief that the land belongs to the people and not to a ruler alone.
 Also, after the revolution, all professions were open to all male applicants, so that the most ambitious and best could succeed.
 The same goes for the military, because instead of class-based army ranks, the army ranks were now based on caliber.
