 Muhammad was very interested in things beyond this everyday life. He often visited a cave known as "Hira" on the mountain of "Nur" (Light) to meditate.
 The cave itself has survived the ages and offers a vivid picture of Muhammad's spiritual inclinations.
 The cave is located at the top of one of the mountains north of Mecca and is completely isolated from the rest of the world.
 In fact, it is not easy to find, even if you know it exists, and once you are inside the cave, you are completely isolated.
 One sees nothing but the clear, beautiful sky above and the numerous surrounding mountains. From the inside of the cave, very little of this world can be seen or heard.
 The Cheops Pyramid is the only one of the seven wonders of the world that still stands today.
 Built in the third century B.C. by the Egyptians, the Cheops Pyramid is one of many large pyramid structures built to honor deceased pharaohs.
 The Giza Plateau, or the Giza Necropolis, in the Egyptian Valley of the Kings, includes several pyramids (of which the Great Pyramid is the largest), several smaller tombs, several temples and the Great Sphinx.
 The large pyramid was built in honor of Pharaoh Cheops and many of the smaller pyramids, tombs and temples were built in honor of Cheops' wives and family members.
 The "spread" symbol looks like a V and the "cut" symbol like a bracket or a square with the lower line missing.
 Up means that you should start at the top and push the bow. Down means that you should start at the frog (that's where your hand holds the bow) and pull the bow.
 Stroking generates a softer sound, while scratching is stronger and more expressive.
 You are welcome to add your own pencil markings; just remember that the printed markings are there for musical reasons, and should be respected as such.
