 To understand the Templars, one must understand the context that led to the founding of the order.
 The period in which the events took place is commonly referred to as the High Middle Ages, an era in European history that spans the 11th, 12th and 13th centuries (1000–1300 AD).
 The High Middle Ages preceded the Early Middle Ages, followed by the Late Middle Ages, which coincided with 1500.
 Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a broad spectrum of ideas in practice, from technology push or technological imperative to the strict sense that human destiny is determined by an underlying logic associated with scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
 Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: first, that the development of technology itself follows a path that is largely beyond cultural or political influence, and second, that technology itself has “effects” on societies that are more inherent than social.
 One could argue that the automobile is inevitably associated with the development of roads.
 However, a nationwide road network for only a small number of cars is not economically viable, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of car ownership.
 The widespread ownership of automobiles also leads to a higher number of accidents on the roads, which in turn leads to the invention of new techniques in the healthcare industry to repair damaged bodies.
 Romanticism had a strong, culturally deterministic element that drew from writers like Goethe, Fichte, and Schlegel.
 In the context of romanticism, it is geography that shaped individuals. Over time, customs and cultures emerged with reference to this geography and these, since they were in harmony with the place of society, were better than arbitrarily imposed laws.
 Just as Paris is known as the fashion capital of the world today, Constantinople was the fashion capital of feudal Europe.
 Its fame as a center of luxury began around 400 AD and lasted until about 1100 AD.
 Its status declined during the twelfth century, which was mainly due to the fact that the crusaders returned with gifts such as silk and spices, which were considered more valuable than the offerings of the Byzantine markets.
 At this time, the title of the world's fashion capital also moved from Constantinople to Paris.
 The Gothic style reached its peak in the period between the 10th and 11th and the 14th century.
 At the beginning, the clothing was strongly influenced by the culture of Byzantium in the East.
 However, the styles in the West are 25 to 30 years behind because of the slow communication channels.
 Towards the end of the Middle Ages, Western Europe began to develop its own style. One of the most important developments of the time was that people, as a result of the Crusades, began to use buttons to fasten clothing.
 Subsistence farming is agriculture that aims to produce just enough food to cover the needs of the farmer and his/her family.
 Subsistence agriculture is a simple, often biological, farming technique that uses saved, indigenous seed from the ecoregion and combines it with intercropping or other relatively simple techniques to maximize yield.
 In the past, most farmers practiced subsistence farming and in many developing countries, this is still the case.
 Subcultures bring together like-minded people who feel neglected by societal norms, and allow them to develop a sense of identity.
 Subcultures can be distinguished from other subcultures in terms of age, ethnicity, class, location, and/or gender of the members.
 The properties that distinguish a subculture as such can be linguistic, aesthetic, religious, political, sexual or geographical or a combination of these factors.
 Members of a subculture often signal their membership by an unmistakable and symbolic style, which includes fashion, habits and jargon.
 One of the most common methods of illustrating the importance of socialization is to rely on the few unfortunate cases of children who, due to neglect, misfortune or intentional abuse, have not been socialized by adults during their childhood.
 "Such children are called ""wild"" or feral. Some feral children were held captive by humans (usually their own parents); in some cases, the child's neglect was due to the parents' inability to accept the child's significant intellectual or physical limitations."
 Wolf children may have experienced massive child abuse or traumatic experiences before they were abandoned or ran away.
 Others may have been raised by animals; some may have lived alone in the wild.
 If it was raised completely by animals, the wild child shows behaviors (within the limits of his physical abilities) that are almost completely in accordance with those of his specific caretaker, such as his fear or indifference towards humans.
 While project-based learning should make the learning process easier and more interesting, "scaffolding" goes one step further.
 Scaffolding is not a learning method, but rather a support that assists individuals in a novel learning situation, such as when using a new computer program or starting a new project.
 Scaffolding can be both virtual and real. In other words, a teacher is a form of scaffolding, but so is the little clipboard man in Microsoft Office.
 Virtual assistance is built into the software and is supposed to question, suggest and explain working steps that the student alone might not be able to handle.
 Children are placed in foster care for a variety of reasons, ranging from neglect to abuse to extortion.
 No child should be forced to grow up in an environment that is not caring, loving and educational, but many are.
 For us, the system of foster care is a piece of security for these children.
 Our foster care system is supposed to provide a safe home, loving caregivers, a stable education, and reliable health care.
 The foster home is supposed to cover all the needs that they did not have in the home from which they were taken.
 The Internet combines elements of mass communication, as well as interpersonal communication.
 The specificities of the Internet have led to additional dimensions in terms of the utility and reward approach.
 For example, "learning" and "socialization" are cited as important motivations for Internet use (James et al., 1995).
 "Personal involvement" and "ongoing relationships" were also identified as new motivational aspects by Eighmey and McCord (1998) when they studied audience reactions to Web sites.
 The use of video recordings led to important insights for the interpretation of microexpressions, facial movements lasting a few milliseconds.
 In particular, it is claimed that one can tell if someone is lying by correctly interpreting minor changes in facial expression.x
 In his article The President's Speech, Oliver Sacks showed how people who have lost the ability to understand language can still correctly assess the honesty of others.
 He even argues that the ability to interpret human behavior may be shared with animals like domestic dogs.
 Research in the twentieth century has shown that there are two pools of genetic variation: hidden and expressed.
 Mutation provides new genetic variations and selection removes these from the pool of expressed variations.
 Segregation and recombination mix the variation between the two pools back and forth with each generation.
 Out in the savannah, it is difficult for a primate with a digestive system like ours to meet its amino acid needs from available plant sources.
 In addition, it has serious consequences if one omits it: depression, malnutrition and ultimately death.
 The most easily accessible plant resources would have been the proteins in leaves and legumes, but these are difficult to digest for primates like us, unless they are cooked.
 In contrast, animal food sources (ants, termites, eggs) are not only easily digestible, but also provide large amounts of protein that contain all essential amino acids.
 Overall, it should not surprise us that our own ancestors solved their “protein problem” in a similar way to how the chimpanzees in the savannah do today.
 Sleep deprivation is the process of deliberately waking up during normal sleep periods and going to sleep shortly thereafter (10-60 minutes).
 This can be achieved by using a relatively quiet alarm clock to gently wake you up, without fully waking you up.
 If you are someone who sets the alarm clock in your sleep, you can put it on the other side of the room so that you are forced to get out of bed to turn it off.
 Another biorhythm-based option is to drink a lot of liquid before bed (especially water or tea, which is known for its diuretic effect), so that you are forced to get up to urinate.
