 Two years after the end of the war, the former Allies were now enemies and the Cold War began.
 It was to last the next 40 years and in reality would be fought out on battlefields from Africa to Asia, in Afghanistan, Cuba and many other places.
 On 17 September 1939, the Polish defence had already collapsed completely and the only hope lay in a retreat and a reorganisation along the Romanian bridgehead.
 These plans were, however, made obsolete almost overnight when over 800,000 soldiers of the Red Army of the Soviet Union poured into the Belarusian and Ukrainian fronts and created them, after they had violated the Treaty of Riga, the Soviet-Polish Non-Aggression Pact and other bilateral and multilateral international treaties in the eastern regions of Poland.
 The use of ships for the transport of goods is by far the most efficient method for transporting large numbers of people and goods across the oceans.
 The Navy's traditional mission is to ensure that a nation is able to project power, and to deter others from doing so.
 One of the most important recent examples of this is the North Atlantic campaign in the Second World War, when the Americans tried to bring manpower and material across the Atlantic to help Britain.
 At the same time, the German Navy tried to stop this traffic mainly with submarines.
 If the Allies had failed, Germany would have been able to conquer Britain and the rest of Europe.
 Goats were apparently already domesticated in the Zagros Mountains of Iran about 10,000 years ago.
 Ancient cultures and tribes began to keep them as livestock to easily obtain their milk, fur, meat and skin.
 House goats were usually kept in herds that wandered on hillsides or other pasture lands.  They were tended by goatherds, much like the more familiar sheep herders; often these were children or adolescents. These grazing methods are still used today.
 As early as the 16th century, in England, they built support rails.
 Although the support rails were only made of parallel wooden boards, they allowed the horses that pulled the wagons to reach higher speeds and pull larger loads than on the somewhat rougher roads of the time.
 Very early on, thresholds were introduced to secure the position of the rails. However, it was gradually recognized that rails that carry a band of iron are more efficient.
 This was common, but the iron caused more wear on the wooden wheels of the wagons.
 Finally, wooden wheels were replaced by iron wheels. In 1767, the first fully iron rails were introduced.
 The first known means of transportation was walking. Humans began to walk upright about two million years ago with the emergence of Homo Erectus (which means “upright man”).
 Their predecessors, the Australopithecus, did not walk upright as regularly.
 Bipedal species are found in Australopithecus fossils from 4.2 to 3.9 million years ago, although Sahelanthropus may have walked upright as early as seven million years ago.
 We can live more environmentally friendly, we can join the environmental movement, and we can even become activists to alleviate future suffering.
 In many cases, this is just like a symptomatic treatment. If you do not want only temporary solutions, then we should find and treat the root of the problem.
 It is really obvious that the world has changed a lot because of the scientific and technological advances of humanity and that the problems of overpopulation and the extravagant lifestyle of people have become more serious.
 After its adoption by Congress on July 4, a handwritten draft, signed by Congress President John Hancock and Secretary Charles Thomson, was sent a few blocks away to the printing shop of John Dunlap.
 Between 150 and 200 copies were made overnight, which are now known as the "Dunlap broadsides".
 The first public reading of the document was given by John Nixon in the Independence Hall courtyard on July 8.
 One was sent to George Washington on July 6, who read it to his troops in New York on July 9. A copy reached London on August 10.
 The 25 Dunlap broadsides that remain are the oldest surviving copies of the document, as the original manuscript did not survive the ages.
 Many paleontologists now believe that there is a group of dinosaurs that survived and are still alive today. We call them birds.
 Many do not see them as dinosaurs because they have feathers and can fly.
 Yet many things about birds still look like a dinosaur.
 They have feet with scales and claws, lay eggs and run on both hind legs like a Tyrannosaurus rex.
 Nearly all computers in use today are based on the processing of information that is encoded in the form of binary numbers.
 A binary number can only have one of two values, namely 0 or 1, and these numbers are called binary digits - or bits, to use computer jargon.
 Internal poisoning may not be immediately apparent. The symptoms, for example, vomiting, are so general that one cannot immediately make a diagnosis.
 The best sign of poisoning by swallowing is the presence of an open container of medication or toxic household chemicals.
 Look on the label for specific first aid instructions for that particular poison.
 The term "bug" is used by entomologists in a formal sense for this insect group.
 This term derives from the ancient familiarity with bedbugs. These are insects that are very adaptable in parasitizing humans.
 Both bedbugs and assassin bugs are nidicol, meaning they are adapted to live in the nest or dwelling of their hosts.
 In the United States of America, there are about 400,000 known cases of multiple sclerosis (MS), making it the most widespread neurological disease in adults of younger and middle age.
 MS is a disease that affects the central nervous system, which is made up of the brain, the spinal cord and the optic nerve.
 Studies have shown that women are twice as likely to develop MS as men.
 A couple may decide that it is not in their own interest or in the interest of their child to raise a baby.
 These couples can choose to adopt a plan for their baby.
 In an adoption, the biological parents give up their parental rights so that another couple can adopt.
 The main goal of science is to find out, with the help of the scientific method, how the world works. This method is indeed the basis of most scientific investigations.
 It is not just about experimentation, where an experiment is a test that is used to eliminate one or more of the possible hypotheses. Scientific research is also guided by asking questions and conducting observations.
 Scientists and philosophers focused on classical texts and especially on the Bible in Latin.
 Aristotle's views on all scientific matters, including psychology, were accepted.
 With the loss of knowledge of the Greek language, the West was cut off from its philosophical and scientific roots in Greece.
 Many observed rhythms in physiology and behavior are often largely based on the presence of endogenous cycles and their production by biological clocks.x
 Behaviours determined by a cycle, which are not only reactions to signals from external cycles, are known in most living organisms, including bacteria, fungi, plants and animals.
 Biological clocks are self-sustaining oscillators that even in the absence of external signals can execute free-running cycles for a while.
 The Hershey-Chase experiment was one of the key pieces of evidence that DNA is a genetic material.
 Hershey and Chase used phages or viruses to insert their own DNA into a bacterium.
 They took two experiments, in which they either labeled the phage's DNA with radioactive phosphorus or a protein in the phage with radioactive sulfur.
 Mutations can have a wide range of effects, depending on what kind of mutation it is, what the significance of the piece of genetic material is, and whether the cells in question are germ cells.
 Only mutations in germ cells can be passed on to children, while mutations elsewhere can lead to cell death or cancer.
 Nature-based tourism attracts people who are interested in visiting natural areas to enjoy the scenery, including wild plants and animals.
 Examples of activities on the ground are hunting, fishing, photography, bird watching, visiting parks and learning about the ecosystem.
 An example of this is visiting, photographing and studying orangutans in Borneo.
 Every morning, people leave small provincial towns by car to go to their workplace and are passed by others whose workplace is at the place they have just left.
 In this dynamic pendulum traffic, all are in some way connected to and support a transport system based on the private car.
 Science now points out that this massive carbon economy has taken the biosphere out of one of its stable states, which has supported human evolution for the last two million years.
 Everyone participates in society and uses transportation systems. Almost everyone complains about the transportation systems.
 In developed countries, you will rarely hear complaints about the quality of water or the collapse of bridges.
 Why do transport systems lead to such abuses, why do they fail on a daily basis? Are transport engineers simply incompetent, or is something more fundamental going on?
 Traffic flow is the study of the movement of individual drivers and vehicles between two points and the interactions that take place between them.
 Unfortunately, the study of traffic flows is difficult, because driver behavior cannot be predicted with one hundred percent certainty.
 Fortunately, drivers tend to behave in a reasonably consistent way; therefore, traffic flows have a certain consistency and can be roughly described mathematically.
 To better represent traffic flow, the relationships between the three most important properties were defined: (1) Flow, (2) Density, and (3) Velocity.
 These relationships help in the planning, design and operation of facilities on the roadway.
 Insects were the first animals to conquer the sky. Their ability to fly helped them to evade predators more easily and find food and mates more efficiently.
 Most insects can fold their wings along their body.
 This gives them a wider selection of small hiding places where they can hide from predators.
 Today, dragonflies and mayflies are the only insects that cannot fold their wings back.
 Thousands of years ago, a man named Aristarchus claimed that the sun was at the center of the motions of the solar system.
 Some people thought he was right, but many believed the opposite: that the solar system, including the sun (and even the other stars) moved around the earth.
 That seems reasonable, since it doesn't seem like the earth is moving, does it?
 The Amazon is the second longest and the most water-rich river on Earth, carrying more than eight times as much water as the second largest river.
 The Amazon is also the widest river on earth, sometimes as wide as six miles.
 As much as 20 percent of the water that flows into the oceans from the planet's rivers comes from the Amazon.
 The Amazon River is 6387 km (3980 miles) long. It takes water from thousands of smaller rivers.
 Although the construction of pyramids of stone continued until the end of the Old Kingdom, the pyramids of Giza were never surpassed in size and the technical perfection of their construction.
 Egyptians in the ancient New Kingdom marveled at the monuments of their ancestors, which were then well over a thousand years old.
 The Vatican City has about 800 inhabitants. It is the smallest independent state in the world and the country with the smallest population.
 The Vatican City uses Italian for its legislation and official communications.
 Italian is also the everyday language of most who work in the state, while Latin is often used in religious ceremonies.
 All citizens of Vatican City are Roman Catholic.
 Basic chemical elements such as gold, silver and copper have been known to humans since ancient times, as they can all be found in their original form in nature and can be extracted with primitive tools.
 Aristotle, a philosopher, put forward the theory that all things are made up of a mixture of one or more of four elements: earth, water, air and fire.
 This corresponded more to the four states of aggregation (in the same order): solid, liquid, gas and plasma. He also put forward the theory that they transform into new substances to form what we see.
 Alloys are basically a mixture of two or more metals. Remember that there are many elements in the periodic table.
 Elements like calcium and potassium are considered metals. Of course there are other metals like silver and gold.
 There are also alloys that contain small amounts of non-metallic elements such as carbon.
 The universe is made up of matter. All matter is made up of tiny particles called atoms.
 Atoms are so tiny that billions of them would fit into the point at the end of this sentence.
 Consequently, the pencil, after its invention, became a good friend to many people.
 Unfortunately, the pencil has been pushed into the background with the advent of newer writing methods, so that it has been pushed back in its status and in its use.
 Nowadays, people write messages on computer screens without ever having to come near a pencil sharpener.
 One can be curious to see what will come out of the keyboard when something newer arrives.
 The atomic bomb is based on the principle that you need energy to combine a nucleus with many protons and neutrons.
 It's like rolling a heavy car up a hill. When the core splits again, some of this energy is released.
 Some atoms have unstable cores, which means that they disintegrate at the slightest or even no provocation.
 The surface of the Moon is made of rock and dust. The outer layer of the Moon is called the crust.
 The crust is about 70 km thick on the near side and 100 km on the far side.
 It is thinner under the mare and thicker under the highlands.
 On the near side, there could be more Maria, since the crust is thinner, making it easier for the lava to rise to the surface.
 Internal theories focus on finding what moves or appeals to people.
 These theories suggest that humans have certain needs and/or desires that are internalized during the course of their adulthood.
 These theories deal with what causes certain people to want exactly the things they do, and what influences in their environment cause them to do certain things or not to do certain things.
 Two popular content theories are Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs and Herzberg's Two-Factor Theory.
 In general, two behaviors can emerge when managers begin to lead their former colleagues. One end of the spectrum is the attempt to remain “one of the guys” (or one of the girls).
 This type of manager has problems making unpopular decisions, carrying out disciplinary measures, assessing performance, assigning responsibilities and holding employees accountable.
 At the other end of the spectrum, you become an unrecognizable individual who has to do everything differently than the team has done and take everything for yourself.
 Ultimately, the team leader is responsible for the success and failure of the team.
 This behavior often leads to disagreements between the leaders and the rest of the team.
 Virtual teams are run according to the same standards of excellence as conventional teams, but there are subtle differences.
 Virtual team members often have the function of a contact point for their immediate physical group.
 They often have more autonomy than traditional team members, as their teams can meet in different time zones that may not be considered by the local leadership.
 The presence of a real "invisible team" (Larson and LaFasto 1989, p. 109) is also a unique component of a virtual team.
 "The ""invisible team"" is the management team to which each member reports. The invisible team sets the standards for each member.x"
 Why would an organization undertake the time-consuming process of introducing a learning organization? One goal for the practical implementation of organizational learning concepts is innovation.
 When all available resources are effectively utilized across all departments of an organization, creativity and ingenuity can emerge.
 As a result, the collective work of an organization in overcoming an obstacle can lead to a new innovative method of meeting customer needs.
 Before an organization can be innovative, the leadership must develop a culture of innovation, as well as a culture of shared knowledge and organizational learning.
 Angel (2006) explains the Continuum Concept as a method to help organizations become more effective.
 Neurobiological data provide physical evidence for a theoretical approach to the study of cognition, thus defining the research area and making it much more precise.
 The correlation between brain pathology and behavior supports scientists in their research.
 It has long been known that different types of brain damage such as trauma, injury and tumors affect behavior and cause changes in some brain functions.
 Emerging technologies allow us to see and explore certain brain structures and processes for the first time.
 It provides us with a lot of information and material to build simulation models that help us understand the processes in our head.
 KI is strongly associated with science fiction, but is a major branch of computer science that deals with behavior, learning and intelligent adaptation of machines.
 Research in the field of AI includes the creation of machines to automate tasks that require intelligent behavior.
 Examples of this are control, the establishment of strategies and time plans, the ability to answer customer diagnoses and questions, as well as handwriting, voice and face recognition.
 Such things have become independent disciplines that focus on finding solutions to problems of real life.
 The AI system is now widely used in business, medicine, engineering and the military, and has been built into numerous software applications for home computers and video games.
 Field trips are an important part of every school class. Not infrequently, a teacher would like to take her students to places that cannot be reached by bus.
 Virtual excursions are a technical solution. The students can view museum pieces from the classroom, visit an aquarium or admire beautiful works of art.
 Sharing an excursion virtually is also a great way to reflect on a trip and share experiences with future classes.
 For example, students at Bennet School in North Carolina design a website about their trip to the state capital every year. The website is redesigned every year, but the previous versions remain online and serve as a scrapbook.
 Blogs can also help improve the writing skills of students. Although students at the beginning of their blogging experience often have sloppy grammar and spelling, this usually changes when there is an audience.
 Since students are often a very critical audience, the blog author makes an effort to improve his writing style to avoid criticism.
 Blogging "forces students to learn more about the world around them." The need to engage the interest of the audience inspires students to write intelligently and interestingly (Toto, 2004).
 Blogging is a tool that inspires collaboration and encourages students to continue learning well beyond the traditional school day.
 The appropriate use of blogs "can enable students to become more analytical and critical; by reacting to Internet materials, students can define their positions in the context of other texts and articulate their own perspectives on particular topics" (Oravec, 2002).
 Ottawa is Canada's charming, bilingual capital and is distinguished by a number of art galleries and museums that present Canada's past and present.
 Further south are the Niagara Falls, and to the north the unspoiled beauty of nature in Muskoka and beyond.
 All these things and more make Ontario what outsiders see as typically Canadian.
 Large areas further north are sparsely populated and some are almost uninhabited wilderness.
 A population comparison that many surprised: There are more African Americans living in the United States than Canada has citizens.
 The East African islands are located in the Indian Ocean off the eastern coast of Africa.
 Madagascar is by far the largest and, in terms of wildlife, a continent of its own.
 Most of the smaller islands are independent nations or belong to France and are known as luxurious seaside resorts.
 The Arabs also brought Islam to the country, and it was very successful in the Comoros and Mayotte.
 European influence and colonialism began in the 15th century, when the Portuguese seafarer Vasco da Gama discovered the Cape route from Europe to India.
 In the north, the region is bounded by the Sahel zone and in the south and west by the Atlantic Ocean.
