 The present-day Casablanca was founded by Berber fishermen in the 10th century BC and was used by the Phoenicians, Romans and Merinides as a strategic port with the name Anfa.
 The Portuguese destroyed it and rebuilt it under the name Casa Branca, only to abandon it after an earthquake in 1755.
 The Moroccan Sultan rebuilt the city as Dar el Beida and it was named Casablanca by Spanish traders who established trading posts there.
 Casablanca is one of the most uninteresting places to shop in all of Morocco.
 Around the old Medina it is easy to find places where traditional Moroccan goods like tagines, ceramics, leather goods, water pipes and a whole range of Tinnef are sold, but that is all for the tourists.
 Goma is a tourist town of the Democratic Republic of the Congo in the extreme east near Rwanda.
 In 2002, Goma was destroyed by the lava of the Nyiragongo volcano, which buried most of the city's streets, particularly the city center.
 While Goma is reasonably safe, any stay outside of Goma should be carefully planned to learn about the ongoing fighting in the province of North Kivu.
 The city is also the starting point for climbing the Nyiragongo volcano and for some of the cheapest gorilla tracking tours in Africa.
 You can use Bodabodas (motorcycle taxis) to get around Goma. The usual (local) price is ~500 Congolese Francs for the short ride.x
 This, combined with its relative inaccessibility, has made "Timbuktu" a metaphor for exotic, far-off lands.
 Although Timbuktu is known as a tourist attraction because of its reputation and has an airport, it is now a poor city.
 In 1990 it was added to the list of endangered World Heritage Sites due to the threat of desert sand.
 It was one of the most important stops of Louis Gates PBS special "Wonders of the African World".
 The city stands in stark contrast to the rest of the country's cities because it has more of an Arabic than an African feel.
 The Kruger National Park (KNP) is located in the northeast of South Africa. It borders Mozambique in the east, Zimbabwe in the north and the Crocodile River in the south.
 The park has an area of 19,500 km² and is divided into 14 different ecozones, each of which supports a different animal life.
 It is one of South Africa's main attractions and is regarded as the flagship of South African National Parks (SANParks).
 Like all South African national parks, the park charges daily conservation and entrance fees.
 It may also be worthwhile to buy a Wild Card, which grants access either to selected parks in South Africa or to all South African national parks.
 Hong Kong Island is the namesake of the territory of Hong Kong and is the focus of many tourists.
 The buildings that make up the Hong Kong skyline were compared with a shimmering bar chart that becomes visible through the presence of the waters of Victoria Harbour.x
 For the best views of Hong Kong, you should leave the island and drive to the opposite shore of Kowloon.
 Most of the urbanization of Hong Kong Island is densely packed on reclaimed land along the north shore.
 This is the place the British colonists made their own. If you are looking for traces of the area's colonial past, this is a good starting point.
 The Sundarbans are the largest mangrove forest in the world and stretch 80 km from the Bangladeshi and Indian hinterland to the coast.
 The Sundarbans were declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The part of the forest that lies within Indian territory is called the Sundarbans National Park.
 The forests are not just mangrove swamps, however – they also include some of the last remaining stands of the mighty jungle that once covered the Ganges plain.
 The Sundarbans cover an area of 3,850 km², of which a third is covered by water and marshes.
 The Sundarbans have been a protected area since 1966, and estimates suggest that there are now 400 Bengal tigers and about 30,000 spotted deer living there.
 Buses run all day from the district-wide bus station (on the other side of the river), with most buses, especially those to the east and Jakar/Bumthang, leaving between 06:30 and 07:30.
 As the buses between the districts are often full, it is recommended to buy a ticket a few days in advance.
 Most districts are served by small Japanese coaster buses, which are comfortable and stable.
 Shared taxis offer a quick and comfortable way to get to nearby places like Paro (Nu 150) and Punakha (Nu 200).
 The Oyapock River Bridge is a suspension bridge. It spans the Oyapock River and connects the cities of Oiapoque in Brazil and Saint-Georges de l'Oyapock in French Guiana.
 Its two towers are 83 meters high, its length is 378 meters and it has two lanes with a width of 3.50 meters.
 The clearance under the bridge is 15 meters. The construction work was completed in August 2011, but the opening for traffic was not until March 2017.
 The bridge is expected to be fully operational in September 2017, when the Brazilian customs posts are expected to be completed.
 The Guaraní were the most important indigenous group inhabiting present-day eastern Paraguay. They lived as semi-nomadic hunter-gatherers who also practiced subsistence agriculture.
 The Chaco region was also home to other groups of indigenous peoples, such as the Guaycurú and the Payaguá, who survived by hunting, gathering and fishing.
 Paraguay, formerly known as the Great Province of the West Indies, was created in the 16th century as a result of the encounter between the Spanish conquerors and the indigenous groups.
 The Spaniards began the colonization period, which lasted three centuries.
 Since the founding of Asunción in 1537, Paraguay has managed to preserve much of its indigenous character and identity.
 Argentina is known for having the best polo team and players in the world.
 The largest tournament of the year takes place in December on Las Cañitas polo fields.
 Smaller tournaments and competitions can also be watched at other times of the year.x
 Information on competitions and sales points for polo tickets can be found at the Asociacion Argentina de Polo.
 The official currency of the Falkland Islands is the Falkland Pound (FKP), whose value is fixed in line with the value of the British Pound (GBP).
 Money can be exchanged at the only bank on the island, which is located in Stanley opposite the FIC West Store.
 The British pound is generally accepted everywhere on the islands and at Stanley credit cards. US dollars are also often accepted.
 On the remote islands, credit cards are probably not accepted, although British and US currency may be accepted; check with the owners in advance to find out which method of payment is accepted.
 It is almost impossible to exchange the currency of the Falkland Islands outside the Islands themselves, so you should exchange the money before leaving the island.
 Since Montevideo lies south of the equator, it is summer there when it is winter in the northern hemisphere, and vice versa.
 Montevideo is located in the subtropics. In the summer months, temperatures above +30 ° C are common.
 Winter can be deceivingly cool: Temperatures rarely go below freezing, but wind and humidity make it feel colder than the thermometer indicates.
 There are no distinct rainy or dry seasons: The amount of precipitation remains about the same throughout the year.
 Although many of the animals in the park are used to seeing people, the wild animals are still wild and should not be fed or disturbed.
 According to the Park Authority, visitors should keep at least 100 yards/meters away from bears and wolves and 25 yards/meters away from all other wild animals!
 No matter how peaceful bison, elk, bears and practically all large animals may appear, they can still attack.
 Dozens of visitors are injured every year because they don't keep enough distance. These animals are big, wild and possibly dangerous, so give them enough space.
 Also be aware that smells can attract bears and other wildlife, so avoid carrying or cooking strongly scented foods and keep a clean camp.
 Apia is the capital of Samoa, located on the island of Upolu, and has a population of just under 40,000.
 Apia was founded in the 1750s and has been the official capital of Samoa since 1959.
 The harbor was the scene of an ignominious standoff of the Navy in 1889, when seven ships from Germany, the United States and Great Britain refused to leave the harbor.
 All ships except for a British cruiser were sunk. Nearly 200 Americans and Germans were killed.
