 Pests can destroy food, cause irritations or, in the worst case, even trigger allergic reactions, poison or transmit diseases.
 Infections as such or dangerous animals that can injure or kill humans with violence are not usually classified as pests.
 Duty-free shopping is the opportunity to buy goods that are exempt from certain taxes and consumption taxes in certain places.
 Travellers whose destination country has high taxes can sometimes save a considerable amount of money, particularly on products such as alcoholic beverages and tobacco.
 The section between Point Marion and Fairmount on the Buffalo-Pittsburgh Highway is the greatest driving challenge, as it often leads through remote, uninhabited terrain.
 If you are not used to driving on country roads, stay alert: steep slopes, narrow roads and sharp curves predominate here.
 The speed limits given are noticeably lower than in the preceding and following sections - usually 35-40 mph (56-64 km/h) - and their strict observance is even more important than usual.
 Yet interestingly, mobile phone coverage here is much better than in many other areas of the route, such as the Pennsylvania Wilds.
 German baked goods are quite tasty. In Bavaria they are quite rich and varied, as well as with the southern neighbor Austria.
 Fruit cakes are widespread, with apples being baked into cakes all year round and cherries and plums being used in the summer.
 Many German baked goods also contain almonds, hazelnuts or other nuts. Popular cakes often go particularly well with a cup of strong coffee.
 If you want to make small but rich pastries, try what is called Berliner, Pfannkuchen or Krapfen, depending on the region.
 A curry is a dish that is based on herbs and spices, along with either meat or vegetables.
 A curry can be either "dry" or "wet" depending on the amount of liquid used.
 In the interior of northern India and Pakistan, yogurt is commonly used in curries; in southern India and some other coastal regions of the subcontinent, coconut milk is commonly used.
 With a choice of 17,000 islands, Indonesian food is an umbrella term that encompasses a huge variety of regional cuisines found across the country.
 However, when the term is used without further attributes, it usually refers to the food that originally came from the central and eastern parts of the main island of Java.
 The Javanese cuisine, which is now widespread throughout the island group, offers a variety of simply seasoned dishes. The Javanese prefer to use peanuts, chili, sugar (especially Javanese coconut blossom sugar) and a range of aromatic spices as flavorings.
 Martingales are aids for the feet of riders, which hang down on both sides of the saddle.
 They give the rider more stability, but there are safety concerns because the rider's feet may get caught in them.
 If a rider falls off a horse and gets his foot caught in the stirrup, he can be dragged along if the horse runs through. To keep this risk as low as possible, a number of safety precautions can be taken.
 First of all, most riders wear riding boots with a heel and a smooth, rather narrow sole.
 In addition, some saddles, particularly English saddles, have safety stirrups that allow a stirrup leather to fall from the saddle as soon as it is pulled backwards by a falling rider.
 The Cochamó Valley – Chile's most important climbing destination, known as the Yosemite National Park of South America, with a variety of large granite walls and cliffs.
 The peaks offer a breathtaking view. Climbers from all over the world discover new routes along the walls, which offer endless possibilities.
 Downhill sports such as skiing and snowboarding are popular sports in which one attaches skis or a snowboard to his feet and descends a snow-covered surface.
 Skiing is a popular travel activity with many enthusiasts, occasionally known as "ski bums", who plan their entire holiday around skiing at a particular location.
 The idea of skiing is very old – cave paintings with depictions of skiers go back to 5000 BC!
 The origins of skiing as a sport go back at least to the 17th century, and in 1861 the first recreational ski club in Australia was founded by Norwegians.
 Ski hiking with a backpack: This activity is also called ski touring or ski hiking.
 It resembles alpine touring skiing or mountaineering, but does not necessarily include it, since the latter is done in steep terrain and requires much stiffer skis and boots.
 Consider the ski route like a comparable hiking route.
 With good conditions, you are able to cover somewhat larger distances than when hiking – only very rarely will you reach the speed of cross-country skiing on well-maintained trails without a heavy backpack.
 Europe is a relatively small continent, but has numerous independent countries. Normally, one would have to apply for several visas and go through several passport controls if one wanted to travel through several countries.
 The Schengen area, however, works in this respect a little like a country.
 As long as you stay in this zone, you can normally cross the borders without having to go through passport control again.
 Accordingly, you do not need to apply for a visa for each of the Schengen member states individually, which saves time, money and bureaucracy.
 There is no universally accepted definition of what constitutes an antique. Some tax authorities define antiques as goods over 100 years old.
 The definition has geographical variations, where the age limit may be lower in places like North America than in Europe.
 Handmade products could be called "antique" even though they are younger than similar products from mass production.
 Reindeer husbandry is an important source of livelihood for the Sámi, and the culture surrounding the trade is also important for many who work in other professions.
 Even in the past, not all Sámi have raised reindeer on a large scale, but have lived from fishing, hunting and similar. They kept reindeer mainly as draft animals.
 Today, many Sámi work in modern professions. Tourism is an important source of income in Sápmi, the Sámi region.
 "Even if the term 'gypsy' is used mainly by non-Roma, it is often perceived as offensive, as it is associated with negative stereotypes and inaccurate perceptions of the Roma."
 If a travel advisory is issued for the country you are visiting, your travel health insurance or travel cancellation insurance may be affected.
 You can also consult the advice of other governments than your own, but their advice is tailored to their own citizens.
 For example, American citizens in the Middle East may be confronted with different situations than Europeans or Arabs.
 Consultations are merely a brief summary of the political situation in a country.
 The views presented are often superficial, general and too much simplified in comparison to the more detailed information that can be found elsewhere.
 A storm is the collective term for any dangerous weather phenomenon with the potential to cause damage, severe social disruption or loss of human life.
 Weather can occur anywhere in the world and there are different types of weather that depend on geography, topography, and atmospheric conditions.
 Strong winds, hail, excessive rainfall and forest fires are forms and effects of weather, as well as thunderstorms, tornadoes, flash floods and tornadoes.
 Regional and seasonal weather events include blizzards, snowstorms, ice storms, and dust storms.
 Travellers are urged to be aware of any type of weather that affects their area, as this can affect all travel plans.
 Anyone planning to travel to a country that is considered a war zone should receive professional training.
 "A search on the Internet for ""Course on hostile environments"" will probably display the address of a local company."
 A course covers all the problems discussed here in much greater detail, usually in combination with practical experience.
 A course is usually between 2 and 5 days long and includes role-playing, a lot of first aid and sometimes weapons training.
 There are numerous books and journals on survival in the wilderness, but few publications on war zones.
 Travellers planning to have a sex reassignment surgery abroad should ensure that they have valid travel documents for their return journey.
 The willingness of governments to issue passports with an unspecified gender (X) or documents that have been updated to the desired name and gender varies.
 The willingness of foreign governments to recognize these documents is also very different.
 The searches at security checks have also become much more intrusive in the time after September 11, 2001.
 Transgender people should not expect their privacy and dignity to be respected when passing through scanners.
 Rip currents are the returning flow of waves breaking on the beach, often at reefs or the like.
 Because of the underwater topography, the backflow concentrates in a few deeper areas and a rapid current can form there to deep water.
 Most deaths occur from exhaustion while trying to swim against the current, which can prove impossible.
 When you get out of the current, swimming back is not more difficult than normal.
 Try to get somewhere where you won't be caught again. Alternatively, depending on your abilities and whether you were noticed, you might have to wait for rescue.
 The return shock comes earlier than the culture shock (the honeymoon phase is not so pronounced), lasts longer and can be more serious.
 Travelers who find it easy to adapt to the new culture sometimes find it particularly difficult to adapt to their home culture.
 When you come home from a stay abroad, you have adapted to a different culture and dropped some of your home country's behaviour.
 When you first traveled abroad, people were probably patient and understanding because they knew travelers have to adjust to a new country.
 One might not expect that even returning travelers require patience and understanding.
 The sound and light show at the pyramids is one of the most interesting attractions for children in the area.
 You can see the pyramids in the dark and while it is quiet before the show starts.
 Normally, you can hear the sounds of tourists and vendors all the time. The history of the sounds and the lights is just like a story book.
 The Sphinx is used as a background and narrator of a long story.
 The scenes are depicted on the pyramids, with the various pyramids being illuminated.
 The South Shetland Islands, discovered in 1819, are claimed by several countries and have the most stations, with sixteen active in 2020.
 The archipelago lies 120 km north of the peninsula. The largest is King George Island with the settlement Villa Las Estrellas.
 Other islands are Livingston Island and Deception, where the flooded caldera of an active volcano provides a spectacular natural harbor.
 Ellsworthland is the region south of the peninsula bounded by Bellingshausen Sea.
 The mountains of the peninsula here merge into the plateau and then rise again to form the 360 km long chain of the Ellsworth Mountains, which is divided by the Minnesota Glacier.
 The northern part or the Sentinel Range has the highest mountains of Antarctica, the Vinson Massif, whose highest peak is the Mount Vinson at 4,892 m (16,050 ft).
 In remote areas without cell phone coverage, a satellite phone may be the only option.
 A satellite phone is generally not a replacement for a mobile phone, since you have to be outside and in clear view of a satellite in order to make a call.
 The service is frequently used by ships, including pleasure craft, as well as expeditions that require data and voice communications.
 Your local telephone service provider should be able to give you more information about the connection to this service.
 An increasingly popular option for people planning to take a year out is to study and take courses abroad.
 This is particularly popular with school graduates, as it allows them to take a year off before university without their studies being affected.
 In many cases, participation in an overseas gap year program can actually improve your chances of getting into college in your home country.
 Usually, a fee is charged for enrolling in these educational programs.
 Finland is a great destination for boating. The “Land of a thousand lakes” also has thousands of islands – in the lakes and in the coastal archipelagos.
 For the Archipelago and lakes you do not necessarily need a yacht.
 Even if the coastal island groups and the largest lakes are actually large enough for any yacht, smaller boats or even kayaks offer a different experience.
 Boating is the national leisure activity in Finland, with every sixth or eighth person owning a boat.
 This is comparable to Norway, Sweden and New Zealand, but otherwise quite unique (in the Netherlands, for example, the ratio is one to forty.)
 Most pure Baltic Sea cruises include a longer stay in St. Petersburg in Russia.
 This means that you can visit the historic city for several whole days, while returning in the evening and spending the night on the ship.
 If you only go on land during the cruise, you do not need a separate visa (as of 2009).
 Some cruises offer Berlin in Germany as a destination in their brochures. As you can see on the map above, Berlin is far from the sea, and a visit to the city is not included in the price of the cruise.
 Air travel can be a frightening experience for people of any age and from any walk of life, especially if they have never flown before or have had a traumatic experience.
 There is no need to be ashamed of this: it is nothing more than the personal fears and antipathies that many people have.
 Learning more about how airplanes work and the procedures during a flight can help some people overcome the fear associated with the unknown or the feeling of not having any control.
 Courier firms are well paid for the fast delivery of things. Often, time is a very important factor in business documents, commercial goods or spare parts for urgent repairs.
 On some routes, the larger firms use their own aircraft, but on other routes and with smaller firms, difficulties arose.
 When they shipped things by air freight, the unloading and customs clearance on some routes could take several days.
 The only way to get it through faster was to send it as unaccompanied baggage. The airline regulations do not allow baggage to be sent without a passenger, and that is where you come in.
 The obvious method of flying first or business class is to pay a thick wad of cash for the privilege (or, better still, get your own company to pay for it).
 That is not cheap: As a rough rule of thumb, you can expect to pay up to four times the normal economy fare for business class and up to 11 times for first class!
 In general, it is pointless to look for discounts on direct flights from A to B even for business or first class seats.
 Airlines know very well that there is a certain core group of flyers who are willing to pay a lot of money for the privilege of getting to their destination quickly and comfortably, and they charge accordingly.
 The capital of Moldova is Chisinau. The native language is Romanian, but many people also speak Russian.
 Moldova is a multi-ethnic republic that has suffered ethnic conflicts.
 This conflict led to the creation of the self-proclaimed Republic of Transnistria in eastern Moldova in 1994, which has its own government and currency, but is not recognized by any UN member state.
 Despite the failure of the political negotiations, the economic relations between these two parts of the Republic of Moldova could be restored.
 The most important religion in Moldova is the Christian Orthodox.
 Izmir is the third largest city in Turkey with a population of about 3.7 million, the second largest port after Istanbul and a very good transport hub.
 The once ancient city of Smyrna is now a modern, progressive and busy business centre, situated on a vast bay and surrounded by mountains.
 The broad boulevards, glass-fronted buildings and modern shopping centres are punctuated by classic red-tiled roofs, the 18th-century market and old mosques and churches, although the city has a more Mediterranean European feel than the traditional Turkey.
 The village of Haldarsvík offers views of the nearby island of Eysturoy and has an unusual octagonal church.
 On the cemetery there are some interesting marble sculptures of pigeons on some graves.
 It is worthwhile to stroll through the fascinating village for half an hour.
 In the north and in the immediate vicinity lies the romantic and fascinating city of Sintra, which became known to foreigners after Lord Byron had described its beauty in vivid colors.
 The Scotturb bus 403 runs regularly to Cabo da Roca and Sintra.
 Also visit the great shrine of Our Lady of the Rosary of Fatima (pilgrimage site) in the north – a place that is world-famous for its Marian apparitions.
 Please remember that you are visiting a mass grave and a place that is of almost incalculable importance to a large part of the world's population.
 There are still many men and women who survived their time here, and many more with relatives who were murdered or worked to death there, Jews and non-Jews alike.
 Please treat this site with the dignity, respect and reverence it deserves. Do not make jokes about the Holocaust or Nazis.
 Do not deface the site by adding or scratching graffiti.
 The official languages of Barcelona are Catalan and Spanish. About half of the inhabitants speak Catalan, the vast majority understand it, and almost everyone can speak Spanish.
 Most signs are only in Catalan, as it is the first official language.
 Nevertheless, Spanish is also widespread in public transport and other facilities.
 Normal announcements are made in Catalan on the metro, but unforeseen disruptions are reported by an automated system in a variety of languages, including Spanish, English, French, Arabic and Japanese.
 Parisians are said to be self-centered, rude and arrogant.
 Even if this is often an inaccurate cliché, one finds oneself in Paris best if one shows one's best side and behaves like someone who is "bien élevé" (well-bred). This will make it much easier to get along.
 The Parisian's harsh exterior disappears very quickly when you show basic manners.
 The Plitvice Lakes National Park is heavily forested, with mainly beech, spruce and fir trees, and offers a mixture of alpine and Mediterranean vegetation.
 Thanks to its numerous microclimates, different soils and alternating altitudes, it has a remarkably large diversity of plant communities.
 The area is also home to an extremely large variety of animal and bird species.
 There are rare fauna such as European brown bears, wolves, eagles, owls, lynx, wild cats and hazel grouse as well as many commonly occurring species.
