 Pre-modern observatories are nowadays usually no longer in operation and serve as museums or educational sites.
 Since light pollution was not as much of a problem during their heyday as it is today, they are usually located in cities or university campuses, which are easier to access than those built in more recent times.
 Most modern research telescopes are huge facilities in remote areas with favorable atmospheric conditions.
 Viewing cherry blossoms, known as hanami, has been a part of Japanese culture since the 8th century.
 The concept originated in China, where peach blossoms were the flower of choice.
 In Japan, the first cherry blossom festivals were held by the emperor only for himself and other members of the royal family in the vicinity of the imperial court.
 "Plants look their best in their natural environment, so resist the temptation to remove even one."
 If you visit a formally laid out garden and take "samples", you will also be thrown out without discussion.
