 In Christianity, Christmas is one of the most important holidays and is considered the birthday of Jesus.
 Many of the traditions around the holiday have been adopted by non-believers in Christian and non-Christian countries around the world.
 There is a tradition of spending Easter night at some open place to see the sunrise.
 There are of course Christian-theological explanations for this tradition, but it could also be a pre-Christian spring and fertility ritual.
 Traditional churches often hold an Easter Vigil on Saturday evening, during the Easter weekend, with the celebrations of the congregations often beginning at midnight, when the resurrection of Christ is celebrated.
 All animals that originally arrived on the islands came either by swimming, flying or by being washed ashore.
 Due to the great distance from the continent, mammals were not able to make the journey, which made the giant tortoise the main prey on the Galapagos Islands.
 Since the first humans set foot on the Galapagos Islands, many mammals have been introduced, including goats, horses, rats, cats and dogs.
 If you visit the Arctic or Antarctic regions in winter, you will experience polar night, which means that the sun does not rise above the horizon.
 This provides a good opportunity to see the Northern Lights, as the sky is more or less dark all the time.
 Since the areas are sparsely populated and light pollution is often not a problem, you can also enjoy the starry sky.
 Japanese work culture is more hierarchical and formal than what Westerners may be used to.
 Suits are part of the standard business attire and colleagues address each other by their family names or job titles.
 Harmony in the workplace is of crucial importance, with the focus being on group performance rather than on praise for individual achievements.
 Often, employees must seek approval from their supervisors for all decisions they make, and they are expected to follow their bosses' instructions unconditionally.
